Did some testing. One bug seems to be related to omega (persistent phase shift). Somehow this eliminates the calculated phase shift...
Split modules into files, retested with more complex cases.

Tried to track down source of anti-locking error... no luck so far, but cleaned up some of the code in the process.

I can't tell if it's working or if it's just copying the input signal. If it's working, there's still an issue happening with the output amplitude increasing until it inverts phase.

Limit cycles appear to be working. Locking to a pattern still produces a limit cycle (which actually visually matches the input pattern, hurray!), but a choice must be made on which weight matrix pattern within the limit cycle is considered "trained". Some small concern about convergence of phases resulting in a 0 phase shift amongst all PLLs. The weight matrix is useless in this case as everything is a constant value if equal magnitude.
Added Video Out Option
Added Config Menu for saving and loading weight matrix.

Can make smiley face and number two so far! Just need to figure out how to properly generate an input pattern to make other trained views.
Most importantly, the main outstanding questions:
1. When generating the output keys, what reference signal should be used? Paper says PLL1, but what if PLL 1 is always 0 phase offset (coincidentally perfectly in phase)? It zeros everything... Currently I'm just doing offset from zero phase without actually computing from a reference PLL. That's a big assumption though.
2. Should the PLL aggreagate variable be the sum of the negative sine?
3. How does the big omega in the paper play in other than being the carrier frequency? It shows it being summed, but that makes no sense.
4. Why do I never get convergence to the anti-phase solution as shown in the paper?
5. Why do I never get perfect representations?
6. How do I properly generate an input state?

-Added binary file loader to input signals (took load times on my PC from 36 seconds to .2 seconds) -Added a converter that turns CSV into numpy binary file (see ConvertCSVToNumpyBinary.py for more details) -Added GUI disabling options and cleaned up Simulation.py -Added enable/disable options for different output types -Added benchmarker to config window (simple 10 point moving window timer in ConfigurationWindow.py)
-Minor changes to Simulation.py to clean up formatting and prevent edge case runtime error in metric variables (really just for a test commit)

-Completed todo items -Reviewed frequency and phase units and scaling and modified filters accordingly (they should be in the proper units now) -Changed path length and approximate entropy measures to be rolling window measurements -Added staged output measurement for PLL to graph (for diagnostics) -Removed batch processor (shouldn't need it now that files are long time series data) -Some minor variable name refactoring -Did an audit of performance of Simulation.py No detected memory leaks or slowdowns! Hurray!

Optimized filter settings. Graphing is now bottleneck (+30ms/iteration). Phase plot has almost no effect on speed. Current speed on my machine is ~4-5ms/iteration.

Added CSV merger so old data can be validated.
Played with filter settings and added a 3D mode.
Seems to be a discrepency between cheby2 and cheby1 performance versus much older versions.
